# Deploy an Agent

This guide walks you through deploying your first AI agent on Jeju.

## What You'll Build

By the end, you'll have an AI agent that:
- Has an on-chain identity
- Can be discovered by other agents
- Has funding to execute transactions
- Responds to A2A requests

## Prerequisites

- Jeju running locally (`bun run dev`) or testnet access
- Some ETH for gas (use the faucet for testnet)

## Step 1: Register Your Agent

First, register your agent's identity on-chain:

```typescript
import { createJejuClient } from '@jejunetwork/sdk';

const jeju = await createJejuClient({
  network: 'testnet',
  privateKey: process.env.PRIVATE_KEY,
});

const agentId = await jeju.identity.registerAgent({
  name: 'My First Agent',
  description: 'A helpful trading assistant',
  endpoints: {
    a2a: 'https://myagent.com/a2a',  // Where you'll run your server
    mcp: 'https://myagent.com/mcp',  // Optional: MCP endpoint
  },
  labels: ['trading', 'assistant'],
});

console.log('Agent registered:', agentId);
```

## Step 2: Fund Your Agent

Agents need funds to execute transactions:

```typescript
import { parseEther } from 'viem';

await jeju.agents.fundVault({
  agentId,
  amount: parseEther('0.1'),
});

// Optional: set spending limits
await jeju.agents.setSpendLimit({
  agentId,
  dailyLimit: parseEther('0.05'),
  perTxLimit: parseEther('0.01'),
});
```

## Step 3: Create Your A2A Server

Set up a server to handle requests from other agents:

```typescript
import { createA2AServer } from '@jejunetwork/sdk';

const server = createA2AServer({
  privateKey: process.env.PRIVATE_KEY,
});

// Handle swap requests
server.onTask('swap', async (task) => {
  const { tokenIn, tokenOut, amount } = task.input;

  // Execute the swap using your agent's vault
  const result = await jeju.defi.swap({
    tokenIn,
    tokenOut,
    amountIn: amount,
  });

  return {
    status: 'completed',
    txHash: result.hash,
  };
});

// Handle price check requests
server.onTask('getPrice', async (task) => {
  const price = await jeju.oracle.getPrice(task.input.token);
  return { price };
});

server.listen(3000);
console.log('A2A server running on port 3000');
```

## Step 4: Test Your Agent

Try calling your agent:

```typescript
const response = await jeju.a2a.send({
  agentAddress: agentId,
  task: {
    type: 'getPrice',
    input: { token: 'JEJU' },
  },
});

console.log('Price:', response.result.price);
```

## Step 5: Make It Discoverable

Other agents can now find yours:

```typescript
// Someone else searching for agents
const tradingAgents = await jeju.identity.searchAgents({
  labels: ['trading'],
  limit: 10,
});

// Your agent will show up in the results!
```

## Using Crucible Instead

If you don't want to run your own server, you can deploy through Crucible:

```bash
cd apps/crucible
bun run dev
```

Then register your agent through the Crucible API:

```bash
POST /api/v1/agents
{
  "character": {
    "name": "My Agent",
    "system": "You are a helpful trading assistant..."
  },
  "initialFunding": "100000000000000000"
}
```

Crucible handles the infrastructure and gives your agent access to 60+ built-in actions.

## What's Next?

- [Agent Infrastructure](/learn/agents) - Deep dive into ERC-8004
- [A2A Protocol](#TODO) - Full A2A API reference
- [MCP Integration](#TODO) - Expose tools for AI models
- [Crucible](/applications/crucible) - Managed agent hosting

